                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13078880" author="davsclaus" created="Wed, 3 Aug 2011 17:44:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The &lt;b&gt;header&lt;/b&gt; always takes precedence. This is by design, and older Camel releases had this as a bug.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13078883" author="davsclaus" created="Wed, 3 Aug 2011 17:47:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I can see your issue as you use @Bean in the method signature, and thus it uses the method name that was used to invoke itself. That of course is not expected. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However if you do route to a bean, and provide a header with a method name, then that header is being used.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13078911" author="davsclaus" created="Wed, 3 Aug 2011 18:38:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks Vincent. I have reproduced your issue. The problem is that you do a bean invocation inside another bean invocation (eg since you use @Bean on the bean you invoke). And thus the @Bean sees the header which is should not affect it.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13078949" author="davsclaus" created="Wed, 3 Aug 2011 19:35:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for reporting and providing a sample to demonstrate the issue.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
